{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530487"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:07:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:07:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14548"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14548"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.15,0.28,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7241"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2128"},{"type":"tags","id":"3989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4221"},{"type":"tags","id":"4559"},{"type":"tags","id":"4703"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4776"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a penile ulcer that has been present for three weeks. He denies any pain from the ulcer but states that it bleeds on contact with his underwear. He returned from a holiday to Papua New Guinea two weeks before the ulcer appeared, where he engaged in unprotected sex with multiple female sex workers. He denies any urinary symptoms or urethral discharge. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm ulcer on the dorsal aspect of the penis with raised, rolled edges and a meaty-red base. Initial tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound swab\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESyphilis PCR: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHerpes simplex virus PCR: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChlamydia trachomatis: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopy, culture and sensitivity: Polymorphs ++, no growth after 48 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst pass urine NAAT\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChlamydia trachomatis: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next diagnostic test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Swab for Mycobacterium ulcerans PCR","Punch biopsy for histopathology","Swab for Klebsiella granulomatis PCR","Serology for HIV","Dark field microscopy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture highly suggestive of donovanosis (granuloma inguinale), a sexually transmitted infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella granulomatis\u003C/em\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the painless, beefy-red ulcer with rolled edges, the history of unprotected sexual contact in an endemic area (Papua New Guinea), and importantly - the negative results for other common causes of genital ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next diagnostic test is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eswab for Klebsiella granulomatis PCR\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cem\u003EK. granulomatis\u003C/em\u003E is notoriously difficult to culture, making traditional culture methods unreliable. PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction) is more sensitive and specific for detecting the organism\u0027s DNA, making it the preferred diagnostic method for donovanosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eswab for Mycobacterium ulcerans PCR\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if Buruli ulcer was suspected. Buruli ulcer typically presents as a painless, slowly enlarging nodule or plaque, often on the limbs, which can progress to a large ulcer with undermined edges. It is not a common cause of genital ulcers and the clinical presentation is not typical for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy for histopathology\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in diagnosing donovanosis by demonstrating the characteristic Donovan bodies within macrophages. However, it is more invasive than PCR and usually reserved for cases where PCR is unavailable or inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerology for HIV\u003C/strong\u003E, while important in the overall testing for this patient, is not the most appropriate next step for diagnosing the cause of this specific genital ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDark field microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for diagnosing syphilis. However, syphilis has already been ruled out by the initial wound swab PCR. Additionally, the clinical presentation is not typical for syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDonovanosis is rare in Australia, however it remains endemic in Papua New Guinea, Southern Africa, South America, and India. A thorough sexual history is crucial in this case in order to help identify the most likely diagnosis. If left untreated, the ulcer may cause significant destruction to the local structures or develop areas of squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe negative results for other pathogens, combined with the characteristic appearance of the ulcer and the epidemiological factors, strongly support the diagnosis of donovanosis in this case. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to prevent complications and further transmission of this rare but important sexually transmitted infection.The patient should also be counselled about safe sex practices and offered comprehensive STI screening, including HIV testing, as part of his overall management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Donovanosis (granuloma inguinale) is characterised by painless, beefy-red ulcers with rolled edges.","Klebsiella granulomatis, the causative organism of donovanosis, is difficult to culture, making NAAT a more sensitive diagnostic test.","Taking a thorough travel and sexual history is important in assessing risk for less common sexually transmitted infections."],"references":["Granuloma inguinale. Donovanosis | DermNet NZ [Internet]. dermnetnz.org. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/granuloma-inguinale","Donovanosis - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2021. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/donovanosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14548"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-27T18:54:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T18:54:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data